<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by Arhu on 12-19-1999 12:18 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Overdoing? Not at all! It's high time that there comes a RPG that challenges you not only by see-and-attack enemies. Well I dreamed a bit  ;) and here are some of my thoughts:

[b]*[/b] First, I don't think it's a good idea to have a text box be popped up each time you see a new creature. It's not just because there probably would be [i]many[/i] different ones  ;), but also because it would hinder a smooth run of events. And those [i]ambushes[/i] wouldn'd really be ambushes, if there would pop up a box right in the moment you see the enemy and have all time of the world to think up a strategy to defend yourself against this [i]dangerous[/i] one. (Say, you walk along a path and suddenly a creature jumps out of his hideout, saying "Booh!!" wanting to shoot some arrows into your err.. butt and then the game pauses..). Instead, it should be possible for the player to learn those things somewhere else (ie from a book, from a chatting person). It could, however, be possible to lurk and spy out an enemy's camp, for example, and use his identfy skill then. So he could use his skill more than one time per enemy.

[b]*[/b] Yes skelletons are dumb. So minor undeads normally just wander around, stay at one place or lie in coffins. But the more intelligent creatures wouldn't just wander around, right? They would possibly rove through the dungeon seeing if all ist normal... They aren't much other than the normal townsfolk, are they? Except that they are somewhat evil... (the player should, however, get a chance to take a rest)
And why should enemies only attack the player together with their own kind? What if a necromancer summons those skelletons and has them encircle the player, for example? Then [i]he[/i] could stay outside the trap and let his minions slaughter the player.  >:)

[b]*[/b] Then, why don't you let the things a character learned about creatures or the world be written in his journy book for later reference, for example? If he identified a creature - whoop! A new entry in his book  :). If he sees a weird event or so - whoop! Yet another entry in his book...
The amount of things he writes in it could depend on his intelligence (he [i]knows[/i] what to write) or his perception (he [i]recognizes[/i] more things)...

[b]*[/b] Oh, and another thing: The trap thing lets me think of the experience points, which the charakter gets. Why should he trap the skelletons if he could kill them and therefore get more experience instead? Thus, he should also be rewarded for intelligent ways of getting rid of his opponents (ie improving other skills than fighting). And btw, I hope there will be lots of [i]real[/i] puzzles in the game, not like those in BG...  :)

[i]Whew[/i]! That was much. Have to retire a bit.

[i]Meow...[/i]
Arhu

[This message has been edited by Arhu (edited 19-12-1999).]</TEXTAREA>
